<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-422-158  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 422 158.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  July 10 1989 n546 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>China plans Wan's arrest. (Stone Computer cofounder R N Wan to bearrested for role in pro-democracy movement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lammers, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Stone Computer Group cofounder RN Wan has been named as one ofseven 'intellectuals' to be arrested for their roles in China'spro-democracy movement.andP;  Stone, China's largest private computercompany, angered Communist Party leaders by supplying computerequipment to students and workers in Tiananmen Square.andP;  Someobservers see an element of personal rivalry involved.andP;  Aninfluential Chinese general whose son works at the state-run GreatWall Computer Corp allegedly became enraged by Stone's success,which made Wan and other key employees wealthy by Chinesestandards and enabled them to recruit many of China's leadingsoftware developers and computer researchers.andP;  The Stone casesuggests that China's leadership is unable to accept the changesin business and political thinking brought about by increaseopenness to Japanese and Western technology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Stone Group (officials and employees).andO;Topic:     ExecutiveChinaInternationalLegal IssuesIntellectual Property.andO;Person:    Wan, R.N. (arrest of).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>